## Migration Impact

All changes maintain backward compatibility while adding significant new functionality. The platform now offers enterprise-grade security, advanced multi-modal capabilities, and professional user experience without breaking existing workflows.

- Core modules import successfully with no regressions
- Individual PRs were extensively tested before inclusion

issue.title: `string.slice` is sluggish on the JavaScript target
issue.body:
I noticed the `string.slice` was slow on JavaScript.

Timing spotchecks

---

```gleam
import gleam/string
import gleam/time/duration
import gleam/time/timestamp

pub fn main() {
  let text = string.repeat("a", 100_000_000)
  let start = timestamp.system_time()
  let _ = string.slice(text, 0, 100)
  echo timestamp.difference(start, timestamp.system_time())
    |> duration.to_seconds
}
```

Erlang:

```sh
> gleam run --target erlang
  Compiling profile_string_slice
   Compiled in 0.21s
    Running profile_string_slice.main
src/profile_string_slice.gleam:9
0.002696667
```

JavaScript

```sh
> gleam run --target javascript
  Compiling gleam_stdlib
  Compiling gleam_time
  Compiling gleeunit
  Compiling profile_string_slice
   Compiled in 0.06s
    Running profile_string_slice.main
src/profile_string_slice.gleam:9
5.79
```

I did a bit of investigation below, and have a potential (silly) idea for a speedup, in the case of pure ASCII strings:

<details>

Looking at the source code

---

```js
export function string_slice(string, idx, len) {
  if (len <= 0 || idx >= string.length) {
    return "";
  }

  const iterator = graphemes_iterator(string);
  if (iterator) {
    while (idx-- > 0) {
      iterator.next();
    }

    let result = "";

    while (len-- > 0) {
      const v = iterator.next().value;
      if (v === undefined) {
        break;
      }

      result += v.segment;
    }

    return result;
  } else {
    return string
      .match(/./gsu)
      .slice(idx, idx + len)
      .join("");
  }
}
```

I noticed it was written to handle unicode characters and that a majority slowdown was happening with the graphemes logic, I'm not sure how to make this faster for unicode, but if we know the string only contains ASCII characters, we could skip this logic:

```diff
export function string_slice(string, idx, len) {
  if (len <= 0 || idx >= string.length) {
    return "";
  }

+  const asciiRange = /^[\x00-\x7F]*$/;
+  if (asciiRange.test(string)) {
+    return string.substring(idx, idx + len);
+  }
+
  const iterator = graphemes_iterator(string);
  if (iterator) {
    while (idx-- > 0) {
      iterator.next();
    }

    let result = "";

    while (len-- > 0) {
      const v = iterator.next().value;
      if (v === undefined) {
        break;
      }

      result += v.segment;
    }

    return result;
  } else {
    return string
      .match(/./gsu)
      .slice(idx, idx + len)
      .join("");
  }
}
```

### Enhancement

For situations where the Server needs to try and access protected resources with access tokens passed by client, we need a way to propagate the 401s from API calls from inside tools.

I tried to do it in my context wrapper and in a middleware but I think the respones are happening in a different layer.

comment.body: At this time, the server is either entirely protected, or not protected at all. We don't recognize HTTP errors coming from inside the server. I think its a good idea to bubble up http errors but it will take some special handling because not every server is http-deployed so I want to make sure we dont inadvertently introduce bad outcomes. Furthermore the MCP layer (the SDK) is going to intercept most errors and convert them into JSONRPC so I'm not sure how much opportunity we have to raise proper HTTP errors here.  /marvin can you research what opportunities we have, if any, to raise e.g. a 401 from inside a tool and have confidence it will actually be captured and returned? or does this require new HTTP middleware in say http.py? Don't open a PR, just return a concise report on how this could work.

issue.title: generate_gir doesn't depend correctly on g-ir-scanner's pymod with string-based includes
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

When the instance of `g-ir-scanner` being used is provided by a subproject, i.e. overridden at configure time, the GIR files for Glib, GObject and GIO depend on g-ir-scanner's pymod ([g-ir-scanner's meson.build](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gobject-introspection/-/blob/main/giscanner/meson.build?ref_type=heads#L110-123), [GLib-2.0.gir's meson.build](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gobject-introspection/-/blob/main/gir/meson.build?ref_type=heads#L244-259)):

```meson
giscanner_pymod = python.extension_module('_giscanner', ['giscannermodule.c'],
  link_with: giscanner_lib,
  c_args: gi_hidden_visibility_cflags + custom_c_args,
  include_directories : configinc,
  dependencies: [
    glib_dep,
    gobject_dep,
    gio_dep,
    gmodule_dep,
    python_ext_dep,
  ],
  install: true,
  install_dir: giscannerdir,
)
```

```meson
glib_gir = custom_target('gir-glib',
  input: glib_files,
  output: 'GLib-2.0.gir',
  depends: [gir_giscanner_pymod, glib_gir_dep, gdump],
  depend_files: gir_giscanner_built_files,
  env: g_ir_scanner_env,
  command: glib_command + [
    '--cflags-begin'] + glib_includes + extra_giscanner_cflags + [
    '-DGLIB_COMPILATION',
    '-DGOBJECT_COMPILATION',
    '-D__G_I18N_LIB_H__',
    '-DGETTEXT_PACKAGE=Dummy',
    '--cflags-end',
    '@INPUT@',
  ]
)
```

However, when [including the GIR by name in later consumers](https://github.com/GStreamer/gstreamer/blob/main/subprojects/gstreamer/gst/meson.build#L316-L326), said dependency is found but not depended on in build.ninja.

```meson
  gir = {
    'sources' : gst_sources + gst_headers + gst_enums + [gst_version_h],
    'namespace' : 'Gst',
    'nsversion' : api_version,
    'identifier_prefix' : 'Gst',
    'symbol_prefix' : 'gst',
    'export_packages' : pkg_name,
    'includes' : ['GLib-2.0', 'GObject-2.0', 'GModule-2.0' ],
    'install' : true,
    'extra_args' : gst_gir_extra_args,
  }
  library_def += {'gir': [gir]}
  # When building statically the information about the gir is going to be
  # consumed by `gst-build` to generate gir files linked against
  # `libgstreamer-full-1.0.so`. We do not build it here as it is currently
  # broken. Once that is fixed we could build it here, even though we would keep
  # creating another gir which links against gst-full.
  if not static_build
    gst_gir = gnome.generate_gir(libgst, kwargs: gir)
    library_def += {'gir_targets':  library_def.get('gir_targets', []) + [gst_gir]}
    gst_gen_sources += gst_gir
  endif
```

```ninja
build subprojects/gstreamer/gst/Gst-1.0.gir: CUSTOM_COMMAND subprojects/gstreamer/gst/gstenumtypes.c subprojects/gstreamer/gst/gstenumtypes.h | E$:/gstreamer/build/subprojects/gobject-introspection-1.84.0/tools/g-ir-scanner subprojects/glib-2.82.4/gio/gio-2.0-0.dll subprojects/glib-2.82.4/glib/glib-2.0-0.dll subprojects/glib-2.82.4/gmodule/gmodule-2.0-0.dll subprojects/glib-2.82.4/gobject/gobject-2.0-0.dll subprojects/gobject-introspection-1.84.0/girepository/girepository-1.0-1.dll subprojects/gstreamer/gst/gstreamer-1.0-0.dll subprojects/libffi/src/ffi-7.dll subprojects/pcre2-10.44/pcre2-8-0.dll subprojects/proxy-libintl/intl-8.dll
 COMMAND = "C:\Program$ Files\Python311\python.exe" "E:\meson\meson.py" "--internal" "exe" "--unpickle" "E:\gstreamer\build\meson-private\meson_exe_g-ir-scanner_bf14194c7c4d8da6dc253debe1ca9e6a6b796d68.dat"
 description = Generating$ subprojects/gstreamer/gst/Gst-1.0.gir$ with$ a$ custom$ command$ (wrapped$ by$ meson$ to$ set$ PATH,$ to$ set$ env)

build subprojects/gstreamer/gst/Gst-1.0.typelib: CUSTOM_COMMAND subprojects/gstreamer/gst/gstenumtypes.c subprojects/gstreamer/gst/gstenumtypes.h | subprojects/gobject-introspection-1.84.0/tools/g-ir-compiler.exe subprojects/gstreamer/gst/Gst-1.0.gir
 COMMAND = "C:\Program$ Files\Python311\python.exe" "E:\meson\meson.py" "--internal" "exe" "--unpickle" "E:\gstreamer\build\meson-private\meson_exe_g-ir-compiler_2176a9610fdfde3e650ba83f0a121afc77da778c.dat"
 description = Generating$ subprojects/gstreamer/gst/Gst-1.0.typelib$ with$ a$ custom$ command$ (wrapped$ by$ meson$ to$ set$ PATH)
```

This means that the build can fail or not depending on whether the pymod has already been linked.

**To Reproduce**

Try building GStreamer with Meson master branch, setting `introspection` to `enabled` and `--force-fallback-for=glib,gobject-introspection`.

**Expected behavior**

Building should still succeed irrespective of the Meson or Ninja version.

**system parameters**
* Is this a [cross build](https://mesonbuild.com/Cross-compilation.html) or just a plain native build (for the same computer)? Native build
* what operating system (e.g. MacOS Catalina, Windows 10, CentOS 8.0, Ubuntu 18.04, etc.) Windows 10 22H2
* what Python version are you using e.g. 3.8.0 -- 3.11.9
* what `meson --version`  1.9.0rc1 commit 070579542f19196abd06beb9e67a9a9012469225
* what `ninja --version` if it's a Ninja build -- 1.13.0

## Purpose
Add a new option `add_partial_tags` to handle creation and update of partial tags for major and major.minor.



## Rationale
It will simplify the CI process for project using partial tags, as it will no more require to add scripts to update those after performing a version bump with psr.

## How did you test?
For now, I only did manual testing. I need more time to setup a fully working test environment and investigate the way the tests are written.
